\section{Real Symmetric Positive Definite Matrix has Positive Eigenvalues}
Tags: Symmetric Matrices, Positive Definite Matrices

\begin{theorem}
Let $A$ be a symmetric positive definite matrix over $\mathbb R$.
Let $\lambda$ be an eigenvalue of $A$. 
Then $\lambda$ is real with $\lambda > 0$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Let $\lambda$ be an eigenvalue of $A$ and let $\mathbf v$ be a corresponding eigenvector.
From Real Symmetric Matrix has Real Eigenvalues, $\lambda$ is real.
From the definition of a positive definite matrix, we have: 
:$\mathbf v^\intercal A \mathbf v > 0$
That is: 
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn	| l = 0
	| o = <
	| r = \mathbf v^\intercal A \mathbf v
}}
{{eqn	| r = \mathbf v^\intercal \paren {\lambda \mathbf v}
	| c = {{Defof|Eigenvector of Real Square Matrix}}
}}
{{eqn	| r = \lambda \paren {\mathbf v^\intercal \mathbf v}
}}
{{eqn	| r = \lambda \paren {\mathbf v \cdot \mathbf v}
	| c = {{Defof|Dot Product}}
}}
{{eqn	| r = \lambda \norm {\mathbf v}^2
	| c = Dot Product of Vector with Itself
}}
{{end-eqn}}
From Euclidean Space is Normed Space, we have: 
:$\norm {\mathbf v}^2 > 0$
so:
:$\lambda > 0$
{{qed}}
Category:Symmetric Matrices
